# jq filter language

A jq program is a pipeline of filters that each take one JSON value and emit
zero or more. The default filter is the identity `.`. This is the grammar the
@search/jq tool runs; it is its own language, not shell.

## Accessing values

| Filter | Yields |
|--------|--------|
| `.` | the input unchanged |
| `.foo` / `.foo.bar` | a field, then a nested field |
| `.["foo"]` | a field whose name needs quoting |
| `.foo?` | the field, or nothing if not an object |
| `.[0]` / `.[-1]` | array element by index (negative from end) |
| `.[]` | every value of an array or object, streamed |
| `.[2:5]` | array slice |

## Combining and transforming

| Filter | Does |
|--------|------|
| `a | b` | pipe a's output into b |
| `a, b` | emit a then b (two outputs) |
| `select(cond)` | keep the input only when cond is true |
| `map(f)` | apply f to each element of an array |
| `to_entries` | object â†’ array of `{key, value}` (inverse `from_entries`) |
| `length` | string/array length, object size, abs of a number |
| `keys` / `values` | sorted keys / the values |
| `has("k")` / `contains(x)` | membership tests |
| `add` / `unique` / `sort` / `sort_by(f)` | aggregate / dedupe / order |

`select` pairs with iteration: `.[] | select(.age > 30)` filters a stream.
Comparison and boolean operators (`==`, `!=`, `<`, `and`, `or`, `not`) build
the condition.

## String interpolation

`"\(expr)"` splices a value into a string: `.[] | "\(.name): \(.age)"`. Combined
with `-r` this prints clean lines instead of quoted JSON strings.

## Flags

| Flag | Effect |
|------|--------|
| `-r` | raw output â€” strings without surrounding quotes |
| `-c` | compact â€” one JSON value per line, no indentation |
| `-n` | start from `null` input (build from nothing) |
| `-s` | slurp â€” read the whole input stream into one array |
| `--arg name val` | bind a shell string as `$name` inside the filter |
| `--argjson name val` | same, but the value is parsed as JSON |

`--arg` is how a query value reaches the filter safely:
`jq --arg q "$term" '.[] | select(.name == $q)'`. `-c` makes output greppable by
@search/rg; `-r` feeds plain text to other tools.
